This set of interaction graphs of a cross-interface connection like the connection between definitions/requirements can be on a different layer than the most useful or most basic definition/requirement graph given the large number of these interaction graphs for each cross-interface connection.
Different axes like optimization/abstraction/interaction/iteration can organize the graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection.

Similar graphs like 'interactions of definitions/requirements' and 'interactions of definitions/intents' can be organized by default as they will look similar, or can be organized by being optimized for position so similar graphs are in similar positions in each graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection, or these similarities can be applied as local axes of the graph of graphs, or similar graphs can have globally similar positions in the graph of graphs like a central position.

These different sets of axes can be applied as different sub-graphs in the graph of graphs, or as different graph layers, or can be integrated by similarity like where there are similarities in graph sequences across the sets of axes, or can be integrated by difference like where the maximum differences are adjacently connectible in a sequence, while these variables don't interfere with the organizing variables of the graph of graphs which indicates a set of cross-interface connections.
These axes can be repeated to identify useful similarities like how organizing a graph of graphs for each cross-interface connection by problem-solving intent is also a way to organize the graph of the set of cross-interface connections.

div.div:
This graph can be organized by problem-solving intent, just like the graph of graphs around each cross-interface connection can be organized by problem-solving intent, to connect the graph to meaning/relevance by connecting it to problem-solving intent, so that connections to meaning emerge from the graph by the problem-solving intent layer.
For example, a graph that is useful for a problem-solving intent has the meaning of being "probably useful for similar problem-solving intents or input/output intents of that problem-solving intent".
So the problem-solving intent structures (implemented as local connections or layers) connect to another layer of meaning, which has its own set of graphs like the intent meaning graph and the problem type meaning graph
